{"key":"post-8515187","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>8515187</id>\n<content>First, dump the blue tub.&amp;nbsp; Mushrooms prefer light in the 'blue' color temperature range, and a blue tub reflects that color light back at you, effectively filtering it from your mushrooms that need it.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Second, air exchange is one of the most important pinning triggers.&amp;nbsp; Rather than being concerned that the crack in your tub will 'let air out' you need to be devising ways to let lots of fresh air IN to the tubs.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Third, Moisture on the sides of the tub indicate a temperature differential between the tub and the outside air.&amp;nbsp; Condensation forms on the warm side.&amp;nbsp; That's why the inside of your windows get condensation in the winter, even though the air in your house is dry.&amp;nbsp; Condensation has &lt;i&gt;nothing&lt;/i&gt; to do with humidity.&amp;nbsp; In fact, it 'steals' humidity from the air in your tub to form on the sides.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Fourth, you're supposed to inoculate around the edges of the cake, right against the glass so the inoculant runs down the glass to coat more of the cake.&amp;nbsp; Inoculate in four places to ensure even, full colonization.&amp;nbsp; However, given enough time, your method will colonize, so this is not your major problem.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Fix the first three problems above and watch your cakes explode.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>8517334</next>\n<prev>8515065</prev>\n<first>8511082</first>\n<last>8518611</last>\n<when>1213296145</when>\n<utime>06/12/08 09:42 PM</utime>\n</post>"}